hrough its standing and participation in regional institutions (especially ASEAN-led or backed institutions) that will further Tokyo's objectives and advance the strategic and security goals of key Southeast Asian states. Japan's capacity to significantly enhance its strategic role in the region ultimately depends on the success of Abe's domestic reforms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChina—Foreign relations—Japan. 0aJapan—Foreign relations—China. 0aJapan—Foreign relations—Southeast Asia. 0aJapan—Foreign relations—United States. 0aSoutheast Asia—Foreign relations—Japan. 0aSoutheast Asia—Strategic aspects. 0aUnited States—Foreign relations—Japan. 4aInternational Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aLee, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981462091840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814620918423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814620918.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK